Child and the work

00:00:51.850 --> 00:00:53.512
that you guys do
around the world.

00:00:53.512 --> 00:00:55.470
SAMANTHA NUTT: So War
Child is an international

00:00:55.470 --> 00:00:57.640
non-governmental
organization and charity.

00:00:57.640 --> 00:00:59.600
And we work with children
and their families

00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:01.490
on the front lines of
most of the world's

00:01:01.490 --> 00:01:04.459
most significant and
intense conflicts.

00:01:04.459 --> 00:01:07.220
So essentially what we are
is we're a protection agency.

00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:08.684
So we go into
environments to work

00:01:08.684 --> 00:01:10.100
with those kids
and their families

00:01:10.100 --> 00:01:14.500
to make sure that they are safe,
that their needs are being met,

00:01:14.500 --> 00:01:17.260
and that they have opportunities
to rebuild their lives

00:01:17.260 --> 00:01:19.670
and rebuild their communities
over the long term.

00:01:19.670 --> 00:01:22.154
The ways in which we do
that, what we focus on,

00:01:22.154 --> 00:01:23.070
we have three pillars.

00:01:23.070 --> 00:01:26.390
So one is education, making
sure that kids in war

00:01:26.390 --> 00:01:28.930
are allowed to maintain
their education,

00:01:28.930 --> 00:01:32.740
catch up on their education,
and grow to be thriving members

00:01:32.740 --> 00:01:33.714
of their community.

00:01:33.714 --> 00:01:36.130
The second part of what we
do-- it sounds a bit technical,

00:01:36.130 --> 00:01:37.120
but it's justice work.

00:01:37.120 --> 00:01:40.220
And so we make sure that
especially in environments

00:01:40.220 --> 00:01:45.510
where girls and young boys
can be sexually assaulted,

00:01:45.510 --> 00:01:47.840
where their rights are
routinely being violated,

00:01:47.840 --> 00:01:51.510
we work to actually promote
and uphold the rule of law

00:01:51.510 --> 00:01:53.857
by training lawyers
and paralegals,

00:01:53.857 --> 00:01:55.440
defending the rights
of those children

00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:57.390
actively within
those communities,

00:01:57.390 --> 00:02:00.354
but also through the legal
infrastructure if one exists.

00:02:00.354 --> 00:02:01.770
And then the third
part of what we

00:02:01.770 --> 00:02:04.150
do we call opportunity, which
is really about making sure

00:02:04.150 --> 00:02:07.240
that families are
economically self-reliant

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:09.930
and have the opportunity to
provide for themselves to try

00:02:09.930 --> 00:02:12.870
to break that cycle
of aid dependency

00:02:12.870 --> 00:02:15.747
that plagues so many
humanitarian catastrophes

00:02:15.747 --> 00:02:17.330
around the world,
but just making sure

00:02:17.330 --> 00:02:20.804
that those families have
resources at their own disposal

00:02:20.804 --> 00:02:22.970
to be able to make the right
kinds of decisions that

00:02:22.970 --> 00:02:25.170
will be suitable for them
and for their children.

00:02:25.170 --> 00:02:26.390
ADAM GREEN: That's
fantastic work.

00:02:26.390 --> 00:02:27.431
SAMANTHA NUTT: Thank you.

00:02:27.431 --> 00:02:29.310
ADAM GREEN: So you work
in some of the most

00:02:29.310 --> 00:02:32.890
miserable and dangerous
places in the world, places

00:02:32.890 --> 00:02:36.250
where there is effectively
active war going on.

00:02:36.250 --> 00:02:38.440
And most of what we
hear is, how do they

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:41.370
get emergency aid-- enough
sutures, enough water,

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:42.770
enough plasma in there.

00:02:42.770 --> 00:02:45.960
How do you guys get
in books, and lawyers,

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:50.665
and actually work with people on
building longer, better lives?

00:02:50.665 --> 00:02:52.040
SAMANTHA NUTT:
Well, I think Adam

00:02:52.040 --> 00:02:53.460
you've hit on a really
good point, which

00:02:53.460 --> 00:02:54.876
is that when we
think about crises

00:02:54.876 --> 00:02:57.710
in other parts of the world, and
especially war, unfortunately

00:02:57.710 --> 00:02:59.100
our memories are pretty short.

00:02:59.100 --> 00:03:01.630
And so we think about
the emergency phase--

00:03:01.630 --> 00:03:04.440
so food, water, shelter,
blankets, vaccination programs,

00:03:04.440 --> 00:03:07.680
the things that you need
to keep people alive.

00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:09.810
But people also need
reasons to live.

00:03:09.810 --> 00:03:13.112
And when wars drag on
as they so frequently

00:03:13.112 --> 00:03:14.820
do-- if you look at
the war in Syria now,

00:03:14.820 --> 00:03:15.780
it's in its sixth year.

00:03:15.780 --> 00:03:18.377
The war in Sudan has been,
apart from a few moments

00:03:18.377 --> 00:03:20.460
where it hasn't been as
intense, has been going on

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:22.690
for many decades now.

00:03:22.690 --> 00:03:24.480
Other parts of the
Middle East, if you

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:27.690
look at the eastern Congo where
it's nearly 20 years, Somalia

00:03:27.690 --> 00:03:31.360
where it's multiple decades,
as those wars drag on,

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:35.070
those gaps and those needs
become that much more enormous.

00:03:35.070 --> 00:03:38.910
And unfortunately, our
capacity to remain involved

00:03:38.910 --> 00:03:42.110
and demonstrate compassion
tends to dwindle

00:03:42.110 --> 00:03:44.500
as those conflicts drag on.

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:47.250
And unfortunately, that's when
the needs become even greater.

00:03:47.250 --> 00:03:50.406
Because you've got kids who have
been out of school for 5, 6,

00:03:50.406 --> 00:03:51.144
10 years.

00:03:51.144 --> 00:03:52.810
You've got families
that have completely

00:03:52.810 --> 00:03:55.660
drained all of their
financial resources,

00:03:55.660 --> 00:03:58.250
that have lost their land,
lost their livelihoods.

00:03:58.250 --> 00:04:02.590
You have a legal infrastructure,
a protective environment

00:04:02.590 --> 00:04:05.940
that has essentially been
destroyed where there may not

00:04:05.940 --> 00:04:06.770
be any police.

00:04:06.770 --> 00:04:09.300
There may not be a functioning
judicial infrastructure.

00:04:09.300 --> 00:04:11.330
So if your rights
are being violated,

00:04:11.330 --> 00:04:14.630
if you're being raped and
abused, you have no recourse.

00:04:14.630 --> 00:04:17.220
And so that's what
War Child focuses on.

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:18.899
And in order to
do that, you have

00:04:18.899 --> 00:04:20.990
to mobilize those
local communities.

00:04:20.990 --> 00:04:22.490
You have to make
sure that they have

00:04:22.490 --> 00:04:24.860
the skills and the capacity
to be able to do the work,

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:26.474
that they have the resources.

00:04:26.474 --> 00:04:28.140
And fundamentally,
you have to make sure

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:30.620
that you have a
long-term vision.

00:04:30.620 --> 00:04:33.800
War is a long-term problem.

00:04:33.800 --> 00:04:38.030
And by continuing to
only plug those gaps,

00:04:38.030 --> 00:04:39.980
we aren't, I think,
fundamentally

00:04:39.980 --> 00:04:42.930
addressing the reasons why
some of these communities

00:04:42.930 --> 00:04:45.920
tend to be locked in that
cycle of violence and poverty,

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:49.140
and frankly, despair
in the first place.

00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:52.170
ADAM GREEN: So you mentioned
the war in the Congo.

00:04:52.170 --> 00:04:54.890
We had the good fortune of
having Malala Yousufzai's

00:04:54.890 --> 00:04:56.430
parents here the other week.

00:04:56.430 --> 00:05:00.270
And he mentioned that
the children that

00:05:00.270 --> 00:05:03.730
are sitting in camps today,
getting no education,

00:05:03.730 --> 00:05:05.930
they are the ISIS of tomorrow.

00:05:05.930 --> 00:05:07.960
They are the wars of tomorrow.

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:09.690
They are the
terrorists of tomorrow.

00:05:09.690 --> 00:05:13.450
The DRC came to be one of the
worst wars in modern history.

00:05:13.450 --> 00:05:15.980
There are an estimated 7 1/2
million kids there who are

00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:19.610
getting no education.

00:05:19.610 --> 00:05:21.210
Is that really the
demographic time

00:05:21.210 --> 00:05:25.600
bomb that Malala's
dad was fearing?

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:27.650
SAMANTHA NUTT:
Certainly, it is true

00:05:27.650 --> 00:05:31.300
that kids who have almost
nothing in environments

00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:35.420
where there is a tremendous
amount of violence, where there

00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:38.070
is recruitment that's going
on by various armed groups,

00:05:38.070 --> 00:05:40.360
militia groups-- in
the case of the Congo,

00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:44.750
it's an inordinate number of
people that are recruiting

00:05:44.750 --> 00:05:46.970
and abducting young
people to fight

00:05:46.970 --> 00:05:50.980
in that conflict in a
climate of absolute impunity.

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:54.060
So certainly, young
people who are unemployed,

00:05:54.060 --> 00:05:58.220
who are not in school, who have
witnessed horrific abuses, who

00:05:58.220 --> 00:06:01.060
have been the victims of
horrific abuses themselves,

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:04.420
they are certainly more
vulnerable to that level

00:06:04.420 --> 00:06:09.550
of recruitment, to that
kind of ideological pull

00:06:09.550 --> 00:06:11.900
that many of those armed
groups will offer them.

00:06:11.900 --> 00:06:13.675
I mean, War Child
knows, even for the work

00:06:13.675 --> 00:06:15.300
that we have done
all around the world,

00:06:15.300 --> 00:06:16.883
that when we have
done skills training

00:06:16.883 --> 00:06:19.640
with young people, when we
have worked with teachers

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:22.230
and other educators to make
sure that they had access

00:06:22.230 --> 00:06:25.572
to education, could go back to
school at an appropriate grade

00:06:25.572 --> 00:06:27.780
level-- because if you're
17 and you've been fighting

00:06:27.780 --> 00:06:29.752
with the militia
group in eastern Congo

00:06:29.752 --> 00:06:31.210
and you're functionally
illiterate,

00:06:31.210 --> 00:06:33.200
you don't want to go back
to being in grade one

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:33.960
with a bunch of six-year-olds.

00:06:33.960 --> 00:06:35.670
I mean, that's
humiliating for you.

00:06:35.670 --> 00:06:37.140
So it becomes a huge barrier.

00:06:37.140 --> 00:06:39.617
So yes, education is
critically important.

00:06:39.617 --> 00:06:40.950
It's not the only thing, though.

00:06:40.950 --> 00:06:44.050
Economic development becomes
critically important.

00:06:44.050 --> 00:06:46.740
Making sure that their
psychological needs are being

00:06:46.740 --> 00:06:49.840
addressed and that
overarching framework

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:53.460
of a lack of accountability is
one of the biggest challenges,

00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:54.015
too.

00:06:54.015 --> 00:06:56.640
ADAM GREEN: Yeah, you're make in
your book a pretty strong case

00:06:56.640 --> 00:06:58.460
that on the Venn
diagram of humanity

00:06:58.460 --> 00:07:03.120
where cheap, small arms and
idle young men intersect

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:04.910
is a recipe for war.

00:07:04.910 --> 00:07:07.980
So bringing education
in hopefully

00:07:07.980 --> 00:07:11.610
pulls the idle young men
out of that equation.

00:07:11.610 --> 00:07:15.530
But how far can you
get when AK-47s cost

00:07:15.530 --> 00:07:17.820
$10 in a lot of these places?

00:07:17.820 --> 00:07:19.080
Education is a huge part.

00:07:19.080 --> 00:07:21.225
What about arms control?

00:07:21.225 --> 00:07:23.350
SAMANTHA NUTT: Arms control
is absolutely critical.

00:07:23.350 --> 00:07:27.350
And I think that it's
especially important right now

00:07:27.350 --> 00:07:28.600
that we talk about this issue.

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:32.070
When you look at the rise
of ISIS in the Middle East,

00:07:32.070 --> 00:07:35.480
if you look at even the
devastating attacks that

00:07:35.480 --> 00:07:37.930
have taken place in
the United States,

00:07:37.930 --> 00:07:42.620
even in Orlando, Florida,
the easy availability

00:07:42.620 --> 00:07:45.530
of automatic and
semi-automatic weapons--

00:07:45.530 --> 00:07:50.220
small arms more generally--
creates both opportunity

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:54.550
and means for those
who seek to destroy

00:07:54.550 --> 00:07:57.120
and harm to be able to do so.

00:07:57.120 --> 00:07:59.050
And the proliferation
of small arms,

00:07:59.050 --> 00:08:01.140
especially in
unstable environments,

00:08:01.140 --> 00:08:03.970
is I think one of the
single greatest threats

00:08:03.970 --> 00:08:06.590
to public health and global
peace and security in existence

00:08:06.590 --> 00:08:07.540
in the world today.

00:08:07.540 --> 00:08:11.780
We have seen a dramatic increase
in the sale of those arms

00:08:11.780 --> 00:08:14.310
and the manufacturing of
those weapons since September

00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:18.730
11th over the past now
more than 15 years.

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:21.180
And so if you have a
lawless environment where

00:08:21.180 --> 00:08:23.190
there is very little
employment where

00:08:23.190 --> 00:08:25.170
you've got half the
population roughly

00:08:25.170 --> 00:08:29.720
that is under the age of
30, and in some cases,

00:08:29.720 --> 00:08:32.159
under the age of
18, you are going

00:08:32.159 --> 00:08:34.760
to have a situation
where people will take up

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:38.360
arms to resolve grievances,
to earn an income,

00:08:38.360 --> 00:08:44.000
and to express their will and
their particular ideology.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.950
So the arms, in
and of themselves,

00:08:46.950 --> 00:08:52.810
I mean, adding that
into the equation

00:08:52.810 --> 00:08:57.780
is one of the hardest issues
to address in a war zone.

00:08:57.780 --> 00:09:00.050
Disarmament is absolutely
critical to peace

00:09:00.050 --> 00:09:01.080
and prosperity.

00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:03.770
ADAM GREEN: And a lot of
the talk about armament

00:09:03.770 --> 00:09:06.140
revolves around the
locations where the arms are.

00:09:06.140 --> 00:09:10.420
But most of those guns are not
coming from sub-Saharan Africa

00:09:10.420 --> 00:09:11.337
or the Middle East.

00:09:11.337 --> 00:09:13.670
They're manufactured within
a couple kilometers of where

00:09:13.670 --> 00:09:14.960
we're sitting right now.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:18.760
The United States is the largest
arms exporter in the world.

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:22.020
And very recently with the
LAV deal in Saudi Arabia,

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:23.754
Canada had the
dubious distinction

00:09:23.754 --> 00:09:26.420
of being declared the number two
arms dealer in the Middle East.

00:09:26.420 --> 00:09:26.660
SAMANTHA NUTT: We did.

00:09:26.660 --> 00:09:28.740
We just jumped to
number two, yeah.

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:31.160
ADAM GREEN: So does that
talk need to happen here?

00:09:31.160 --> 00:09:34.270
Usually when we talk about
arms control and proliferation,

00:09:34.270 --> 00:09:35.620
it's on the nuclear scale.

00:09:35.620 --> 00:09:38.320
Like our militaries tend
to be obsessed with state

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:40.040
versus state conflict.

00:09:40.040 --> 00:09:44.170
We're spending a trillion
dollars on the next fighter jet

00:09:44.170 --> 00:09:45.710
program, the F-35.

00:09:45.710 --> 00:09:48.730
That's the entire aid budget
of the world, roughly--

00:09:48.730 --> 00:09:51.300
the NGO budget.

00:09:51.300 --> 00:09:53.290
At what point does
arms control need

00:09:53.290 --> 00:09:56.800
to start talking about
like 20 caliber things that

00:09:56.800 --> 00:10:00.810
sit in someone's purse
in Texas but then can

00:10:00.810 --> 00:10:05.132
be used to end dozens of lives
in somewhere like Sierra Leone?

00:10:05.132 --> 00:10:06.590
SAMANTHA NUTT:
Well, I think you've

00:10:06.590 --> 00:10:10.715
asked-- there are multiple
pieces to that question, which

00:10:10.715 --> 00:10:13.340
is I think a very,
very important one.

00:10:13.340 --> 00:10:17.720
On the issue of small arms
being available and accessible,

00:10:17.720 --> 00:10:19.630
the problem with small
arms, many of them--

00:10:19.630 --> 00:10:21.080
look at the Kalashnikov rifle.

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:22.900
They're virtually
indestructible.

00:10:22.900 --> 00:10:25.270
They are the preferred
weapon of child soldiers.

00:10:25.270 --> 00:10:26.040
ADAM GREEN: Yeah, it's
made to be buried in sand

00:10:26.040 --> 00:10:27.000
and still keep working.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:27.865
SAMANTHA NUTT: And so
if you make it here,

00:10:27.865 --> 00:10:29.040
or you make it
the United States,

00:10:29.040 --> 00:10:31.290
or it's made in Russia, or
in China, or wherever else,

00:10:31.290 --> 00:10:33.280
once it gets into an
international market,

00:10:33.280 --> 00:10:35.850
that is rarely its last stop.

00:10:35.850 --> 00:10:37.844
And some of the ones
that I have seen,

00:10:37.844 --> 00:10:39.260
and frankly, some
of the ones that

00:10:39.260 --> 00:10:42.630
have been pointed at me
over the years by young men,

00:10:42.630 --> 00:10:45.200
have been weapons that were
made even in the '50s and '60s.

00:10:45.200 --> 00:10:47.880
They're very easy for
kids to load, and reload,

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:49.440
and to be trained to use.

00:10:49.440 --> 00:10:53.470
So any weapon like that
that enters the marketplace,

00:10:53.470 --> 00:10:54.981
it is a permanent problem.

00:10:54.981 --> 00:10:56.230
It is not a temporary problem.

00:10:56.230 --> 00:10:58.000
So that's one piece of it.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:02.470
In terms of who contributes to
that, if you look at all weapon

00:11:02.470 --> 00:11:06.060
sales-- so that includes
everything-- roughly 80%

00:11:06.060 --> 00:11:10.520
of all weapons that are sold
in the world are manufactured

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:13.660
by-- the United States
is roughly half.

00:11:13.660 --> 00:11:18.656
But then usually, it's England,
Germany, France, Russia, China.

00:11:18.656 --> 00:11:21.030
So roughly 80% of them come
from none other than the five

00:11:21.030 --> 00:11:23.450
permanent members of the United
Nations Security Council,

00:11:23.450 --> 00:11:25.090
plus Germany.

00:11:25.090 --> 00:11:29.206
Unfortunately now, Canada is
inching into that equation.

00:11:29.206 --> 00:11:30.830
And I think it's
something that we have

00:11:30.830 --> 00:11:32.960
to consider very carefully.

00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:35.990
Because it does,
I think, undermine

00:11:35.990 --> 00:11:37.570
our international reputation.

00:11:37.570 --> 00:11:39.820
And we as Canadians can
sometimes-- you know,

00:11:39.820 --> 00:11:42.560
we think that we're the
world's peacekeepers

00:11:42.560 --> 00:11:44.900
and that we have this
reputation around the world

00:11:44.900 --> 00:11:45.880
of human rights.

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:47.796
ADAM GREEN: We're like
number 58 on the list--

00:11:47.796 --> 00:11:49.920
SAMANTHA NUTT: Yeah, and
we're not that anymore.

00:11:49.920 --> 00:11:54.390
And if we want to have that
kind of prominence on the world

00:11:54.390 --> 00:11:57.930
stage, and that credibility
and that reputation,

00:11:57.930 --> 00:12:02.080
then I personally think that
we have to really question

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:05.050
whether or not our
arms exports are

00:12:05.050 --> 00:12:09.520
consistent with those
values of promoting peace,

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:10.850
and security, and human rights.

00:12:10.850 --> 00:12:13.060
Because you can go to any
war zone around the world

00:12:13.060 --> 00:12:14.780
and know that that
is not the case.

00:12:14.780 --> 00:12:18.139
ADAM GREEN: So until we can
do that, do you feel like you

00:12:18.139 --> 00:12:19.680
guys at War Child
are kind of bailing

00:12:19.680 --> 00:12:23.830
the Titanic with a bucket as
you try to educate people out

00:12:23.830 --> 00:12:28.220
of this but almost
unlimited free weapons are

00:12:28.220 --> 00:12:31.374
coming in the other side?

00:12:31.374 --> 00:12:33.540
SAMANTHA NUTT: I think I
would look at that metaphor

00:12:33.540 --> 00:12:34.530
slightly differently.

00:12:34.530 --> 00:12:37.430
I feel like sometimes, you're
on the deck of the Titanic,

00:12:37.430 --> 00:12:38.930
and you can see the iceberg.

00:12:38.930 --> 00:12:42.850
You see kids and
the Syrian refugees

00:12:42.850 --> 00:12:45.530
living in camps,
who are becoming

00:12:45.530 --> 00:12:48.210
increasingly despondent because
they don't have opportunity.

00:12:48.210 --> 00:12:50.790
You see southern
Sudanese families

00:12:50.790 --> 00:12:54.990
who are selling their
children into arms groups

00:12:54.990 --> 00:12:56.491
because they've run
out of resources

00:12:56.491 --> 00:12:58.281
and because they're
increasingly desperate.

00:12:58.281 --> 00:13:00.450
So you feel like you're on
the deck of the Titanic.

00:13:00.450 --> 00:13:01.830
You can see the iceberg.

00:13:01.830 --> 00:13:03.205
And you're going,
hey, everybody.

00:13:03.205 --> 00:13:04.020
See iceberg.

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:07.140
See the iceberg, right?

00:13:07.140 --> 00:13:09.160
And yet, it's not
enough to change course.

00:13:09.160 --> 00:13:12.370
And that's the part that's
incredibly frustrating

00:13:12.370 --> 00:13:15.590
for me and I think for
us as an organization.

00:13:15.590 --> 00:13:21.660
Because you can feel it on the
ground when it's happening.

00:13:21.660 --> 00:13:26.390
You can feel that shift, that
moment when people transition

00:13:26.390 --> 00:13:30.740
from being hopeful to that
sense of hopelessness, that

00:13:30.740 --> 00:13:33.180
sense that the world has
forgotten them, that nobody

00:13:33.180 --> 00:13:37.140
cares about what's
happening to them, that when

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:40.080
that anger and that
resentment begin to build,

00:13:40.080 --> 00:13:43.160
when they feel
increasingly desperate.

00:13:43.160 --> 00:13:46.240
And it's no surprise
then that almost a year

00:13:46.240 --> 00:13:49.370
within that moment,
you start to see people

00:13:49.370 --> 00:13:51.930
putting their toddlers
into rubber dinghies

00:13:51.930 --> 00:13:55.570
and trying to make it
across the Mediterranean Sea

00:13:55.570 --> 00:13:58.147
to get them to safety.

00:13:58.147 --> 00:13:59.730
ADAM GREEN: Yeah,
when that's the best

00:13:59.730 --> 00:14:01.610
option for your
family, you things

00:14:01.610 --> 00:14:03.334
are unspeakably horrible.

00:14:03.334 --> 00:14:04.500
SAMANTHA NUTT: That's right.

00:14:04.500 --> 00:14:05.600
That's the problem.

00:14:05.600 --> 00:14:08.600
ADAM GREEN: So your
book is full of

00:14:08.600 --> 00:14:11.900
unbelievably harrowing
stories, things

00:14:11.900 --> 00:14:13.150
that you've gone through.

00:14:13.150 --> 00:14:14.650
One of the things
that struck me was

00:14:14.650 --> 00:14:19.734
the number of whip-smart,
incredibly brave educated women

00:14:19.734 --> 00:14:22.150
from around the world that
you've worked with who have met

00:14:22.150 --> 00:14:25.410
with horrible untimely ends.

00:14:25.410 --> 00:14:29.640
You make a really good case
for the education of women

00:14:29.640 --> 00:14:30.955
and girls around the world.

00:14:30.955 --> 00:14:32.830
As a father of two little
girls, I don't even

00:14:32.830 --> 00:14:35.160
think it's up for debate.

00:14:35.160 --> 00:14:37.890
But how risky is it?

00:14:37.890 --> 00:14:40.584
As we educate them, are
we sending more people

00:14:40.584 --> 00:14:42.500
to the slaughter if we're
not educating people

00:14:42.500 --> 00:14:46.170
on the other side, educating
the angry young men with the $10

00:14:46.170 --> 00:14:51.150
automatic rifles, as to what
society could and should look

00:14:51.150 --> 00:14:53.112
like if everyone was equal?

00:14:53.112 --> 00:14:54.570
SAMANTHA NUTT: You
have to do both.

00:14:54.570 --> 00:14:57.100
You don't have to do one
at the exclusion of others.

00:14:57.100 --> 00:14:59.160
So educating girls
doesn't mean that that

00:14:59.160 --> 00:15:01.887
comes at the expense
of educating boys.

00:15:01.887 --> 00:15:03.720
And we found that and
War Child's found that

00:15:03.720 --> 00:15:05.240
with our work all
around the world.

00:15:05.240 --> 00:15:07.620
If you're not
investing in what we

00:15:07.620 --> 00:15:09.390
call community-based
sensitization-- going

00:15:09.390 --> 00:15:12.060
into those communities,
talking about the value

00:15:12.060 --> 00:15:15.180
of girls' education,
demonstrating the importance

00:15:15.180 --> 00:15:18.220
of women's economic
empowerment, proving

00:15:18.220 --> 00:15:21.990
that to those communities
by having those women return

00:15:21.990 --> 00:15:23.910
and they do become very
productive members.

00:15:23.910 --> 00:15:28.510
And slowly, you see people's
minds and attitudes change.

00:15:28.510 --> 00:15:31.250
And you can't go in there
with this giant sort

00:15:31.250 --> 00:15:34.730
of imperialist agenda and your
finger wagging, and saying,

00:15:34.730 --> 00:15:36.670
it's got to be this
way and that's wrong.

00:15:36.670 --> 00:15:38.530
Because if you do that,
you're going to be shut out

00:15:38.530 --> 00:15:39.113
and shut down.

00:15:39.113 --> 00:15:41.670
And you may in fact put many
of those young girls or women

00:15:41.670 --> 00:15:44.260
that you want to be
helping at risk by virtue

00:15:44.260 --> 00:15:45.860
of behaving in that fashion.

00:15:45.860 --> 00:15:47.740
ADAM GREEN: And there's
been some of that.

00:15:47.740 --> 00:15:53.210
Madonna had an education
effort that ended in flames,

00:15:53.210 --> 00:15:57.552
and Oprah and a few others.

00:15:57.552 --> 00:15:59.260
You offer some pretty
withering criticism

00:15:59.260 --> 00:16:01.843
in your book of people who just
come in with an outside agenda

00:16:01.843 --> 00:16:04.899
into a local area and say,
this is how it should be.

00:16:04.899 --> 00:16:06.940
How do you guys operate
differently at War Child?

00:16:06.940 --> 00:16:08.731
How do you make sure
you're not doing that?

00:16:08.731 --> 00:16:11.146
SAMANTHA NUTT: Well, for us,
98% of our staff are local.

00:16:11.146 --> 00:16:13.270
And we have several hundred
staff around the world.

00:16:13.270 --> 00:16:15.480
So these are folks who
come from war zones who

00:16:15.480 --> 00:16:17.420
are working for us
within those countries

00:16:17.420 --> 00:16:20.450
to build our programs,
to identify the needs,

00:16:20.450 --> 00:16:23.699
to evaluate them, to
make sure that we're

00:16:23.699 --> 00:16:25.490
asking the right
questions and that we have

00:16:25.490 --> 00:16:28.810
that level of community
legitimacy and acceptance

00:16:28.810 --> 00:16:30.580
before we even start.

00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:33.067
We are, as I said, we're not
an emergency organization.

00:16:33.067 --> 00:16:34.900
So we don't go in there
and say, well, we're

00:16:34.900 --> 00:16:36.066
in the business of blankets.

00:16:36.066 --> 00:16:37.360
So here's your blanket.

00:16:37.360 --> 00:16:38.450
That's not what we do.

00:16:38.450 --> 00:16:41.410
We go in, and we will have
a one, two-year process

00:16:41.410 --> 00:16:44.680
of information gathering;
of collaboration;

00:16:44.680 --> 00:16:47.570
of conversation with
local community groups,

00:16:47.570 --> 00:16:49.640
grassroots civil
society organizations,

00:16:49.640 --> 00:16:52.000
UN agencies, other
organizations on the ground,

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.170
to say, OK, what contribution
can we make here?

00:16:55.170 --> 00:16:56.290
What are the needs?

00:16:56.290 --> 00:16:57.560
What needs are not being met?

00:16:57.560 --> 00:16:59.940
What is the overall risk to
children in that community

00:16:59.940 --> 00:17:01.610
by not meeting those needs?

00:17:01.610 --> 00:17:03.330
And how can we help you?

00:17:03.330 --> 00:17:05.790
And I think that that
fundamentally is the question.

00:17:05.790 --> 00:17:08.589
If you go in and say, this is
how we're going to help you,

00:17:08.589 --> 00:17:10.310
that's how aid goes wrong.

00:17:10.310 --> 00:17:14.450
If you go in and say, tell me
about what's going on here.

00:17:14.450 --> 00:17:15.359
How can we help you?

00:17:15.359 --> 00:17:16.790
And you and you
build it, and you

00:17:16.790 --> 00:17:19.740
were critical in that
process, and ask yourself

00:17:19.740 --> 00:17:21.526
the hard questions,
it doesn't mean

00:17:21.526 --> 00:17:22.650
you'll always get it right.

00:17:22.650 --> 00:17:24.390
But it means you're more
likely to get it right.

00:17:24.390 --> 00:17:26.264
ADAM GREEN: So come with
more question marks,

00:17:26.264 --> 00:17:27.657
less exclamation points.

00:17:27.657 --> 00:17:28.740
SAMANTHA NUTT: Absolutely.

00:17:28.740 --> 00:17:30.240
And you see that
in a lot of crises.

00:17:30.240 --> 00:17:32.142
You see a lot of grandstanding.

00:17:32.142 --> 00:17:34.600
And for me over the years, you
know, I've been in this work

00:17:34.600 --> 00:17:35.330
for 20 years.

00:17:35.330 --> 00:17:37.320
It's kind of been the
bane of my existence.

00:17:37.320 --> 00:17:39.750
People who have no experience
in Iraq and they've

00:17:39.750 --> 00:17:41.500
been there for two
days, and they stand up

00:17:41.500 --> 00:17:43.150
and they say, children
are starving here

00:17:43.150 --> 00:17:45.080
And you look at them, and
you go, where the hell

00:17:45.080 --> 00:17:45.663
have you been?

00:17:45.663 --> 00:17:48.040
Yes, they have been starving
there for last 10 years,

00:17:48.040 --> 00:17:49.630
actually, thanks
to the sanctions.

00:17:49.630 --> 00:17:50.350
But--

00:17:50.350 --> 00:17:51.040
ADAM GREEN: Into
the ninth inning.

00:17:51.040 --> 00:17:51.640
SAMANTHA NUTT: Yeah, welcome.

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:54.223
ADAM GREEN: We've been playing
this baseball game for a while.

00:17:54.223 --> 00:17:55.850
SAMANTHA NUTT: That's right.

00:17:55.850 --> 00:17:59.070
ADAM GREEN: You also offer
some pretty heavy criticism

00:17:59.070 --> 00:18:01.450
of well-meaning do-gooders.

00:18:01.450 --> 00:18:05.790
How can we, in the
privileged West,

00:18:05.790 --> 00:18:10.110
help folks that
actually is productive?

00:18:10.110 --> 00:18:14.210
You're pretty critical of
things like voluntourism,

00:18:14.210 --> 00:18:17.214
of ping-pong ball funding
where fund the government that

00:18:17.214 --> 00:18:19.380
funds the UN that then funds
their local region that

00:18:19.380 --> 00:18:20.380
then funds an NGO.

00:18:20.380 --> 00:18:23.560
And by the time someone in
need actually gets the money,

00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:26.560
it's like small
pennies on the dollar.

00:18:26.560 --> 00:18:29.067
What can we do that's actually
effective from this end?

00:18:29.067 --> 00:18:31.150
SAMANTHA NUTT: Well, there
are a number of things.

00:18:31.150 --> 00:18:32.760
I mean, the more
directly you can

00:18:32.760 --> 00:18:35.724
contribute to an organization
that is working on the ground

00:18:35.724 --> 00:18:37.390
and with those
grassroots partners, that

00:18:37.390 --> 00:18:39.473
means that your money is
going to go much further.

00:18:39.473 --> 00:18:41.380
So every time, if
[INAUDIBLE] organization

00:18:41.380 --> 00:18:43.620
that then has an
international arm, and then it

00:18:43.620 --> 00:18:45.590
gets kind of divided
and divided and divided,

00:18:45.590 --> 00:18:47.550
and it will end up
at the field level,

00:18:47.550 --> 00:18:49.280
the impact of your
dollar is diluted.

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:51.030
So that's something
to be very mindful of,

00:18:51.030 --> 00:18:52.160
is to always make sure.

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:55.300
Ask organizations, what is
their programming model?

00:18:55.300 --> 00:18:57.400
Are they a directly
implementing agency?

00:18:57.400 --> 00:19:00.800
Because that's
very, very critical.

00:19:00.800 --> 00:19:03.660
The second piece of it is
so much of our aid money

00:19:03.660 --> 00:19:05.900
is wasted because of one thing.

00:19:05.900 --> 00:19:08.370
And that one thing
is inconsistency.

00:19:08.370 --> 00:19:10.060
Because we see a
crisis in the news.

00:19:10.060 --> 00:19:13.090
We might write a check once,
or go online and donate.

00:19:13.090 --> 00:19:15.750
And then here we are five, six,
seven years later going, well,

00:19:15.750 --> 00:19:18.190
why don't things get any
better in places like Haiti?

00:19:18.190 --> 00:19:19.810
I mean, these kinds
of challenges,

00:19:19.810 --> 00:19:21.880
you're really talking
about structural deficits.

00:19:21.880 --> 00:19:24.330
And like anything
else, it takes time.

00:19:24.330 --> 00:19:26.930
And so we know here, if you're
talking about education,

00:19:26.930 --> 00:19:30.020
it's not enough to send a kid to
school for a week, or a month,

00:19:30.020 --> 00:19:30.840
or even a year.

00:19:30.840 --> 00:19:32.690
It is a long-term investment.

00:19:32.690 --> 00:19:34.910
So you're far better
off as a donor

00:19:34.910 --> 00:19:36.940
giving a-- and
this is always when

00:19:36.940 --> 00:19:39.200
my head director of
development has a heart attack.

00:19:39.200 --> 00:19:42.250
But now he's going,
don't say this.

00:19:42.250 --> 00:19:45.470
But you're far better off
giving a smaller amount of money

00:19:45.470 --> 00:19:48.900
on a regular basis than you
are writing a check once

00:19:48.900 --> 00:19:50.540
and then forgetting about it.

00:19:50.540 --> 00:19:52.250
It allows organizations
to properly

00:19:52.250 --> 00:19:55.695
plan, to implement in areas that
the world has often forgotten

00:19:55.695 --> 00:19:57.620
and has shown less interest in.

00:19:57.620 --> 00:20:01.620
It allows you to direct those
resources to the highest need

00:20:01.620 --> 00:20:04.310
environments and
not be so subjected

00:20:04.310 --> 00:20:08.360
to the whims and mercies of
the media cycle, for example.

00:20:08.360 --> 00:20:09.710
So that's one way to do it.

00:20:09.710 --> 00:20:11.996
Don't give things
like hard goods--

00:20:11.996 --> 00:20:13.620
clothes, and books,
and all that stuff.

00:20:13.620 --> 00:20:15.115
It won't get there
in time to be useful.

00:20:15.115 --> 00:20:16.900
It's too expensive to
ship and distribute.

00:20:16.900 --> 00:20:18.540
ADAM GREEN: Yeah, cash flies
a lot cheaper than books.

00:20:18.540 --> 00:20:20.041
SAMANTHA NUTT: Cash
is a lot better.

00:20:20.041 --> 00:20:21.915
You know, it's a much
better way of doing it.

00:20:21.915 --> 00:20:23.380
And in fact, many
organizations now

00:20:23.380 --> 00:20:25.490
are looking at cash
vouchers for refugees

00:20:25.490 --> 00:20:27.660
because then they can
make their own decisions

00:20:27.660 --> 00:20:30.000
around what their family needs.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:31.807
We have this very
paternalistic approach.

00:20:31.807 --> 00:20:33.390
It's like, no, you're
going to have 10

00:20:33.390 --> 00:20:34.752
bags of rice and six blankets.

00:20:34.752 --> 00:20:36.210
And a lot of those
refugee families

00:20:36.210 --> 00:20:38.190
are sitting there saying,
actually, I don't eat rice

00:20:38.190 --> 00:20:39.230
and I've got enough blankets.

00:20:39.230 --> 00:20:40.200
But that's not how we do it.

00:20:40.200 --> 00:20:40.320
ADAM GREEN: It's very hot here.

00:20:40.320 --> 00:20:41.400
I don't need more blankets.

00:20:41.400 --> 00:20:43.066
SAMANTHA NUTT: And
so now we're changing

00:20:43.066 --> 00:20:47.420
that attitude and making it
certainly more empowering,

00:20:47.420 --> 00:20:50.600
but also some recognizing the
value of cash contributions.

00:20:50.600 --> 00:20:56.580
And gifts in kind like labor are
extremely valuable, especially

00:20:56.580 --> 00:20:59.960
to organizations that might
have headquarters locally.

00:20:59.960 --> 00:21:01.730
People have various
skills that they

00:21:01.730 --> 00:21:03.810
can bring to our organization.

00:21:03.810 --> 00:21:06.690
But that volunteer work is
most helpful to us here.

00:21:06.690 --> 00:21:09.750
Unless you are a
seasoned expert who

00:21:09.750 --> 00:21:12.240
understands development,
understands the context,

00:21:12.240 --> 00:21:14.539
understands the risks
involved, frankly,

00:21:14.539 --> 00:21:16.830
when you're going overseas
and doing this kind of work,

00:21:16.830 --> 00:21:18.670
you might be taking
those opportunities away

00:21:18.670 --> 00:21:20.086
from local community
groups, which

00:21:20.086 --> 00:21:21.470
is something to be mindful of.

00:21:21.470 --> 00:21:23.750
A lot of it is busy
work philanthropy.

00:21:23.750 --> 00:21:26.080
Do you really need to go
and repaint that classroom?

00:21:26.080 --> 00:21:28.080
Or is there somebody
else that, with money

00:21:28.080 --> 00:21:30.820
you save on your ticket,
could be hired locally--

00:21:30.820 --> 00:21:32.370
ADAM GREEN: Perhaps
a local painter.

00:21:32.370 --> 00:21:34.304
SAMANTHA NUTT: --to
paint that classroom.

00:21:34.304 --> 00:21:35.720
And then the second
piece of it is

00:21:35.720 --> 00:21:38.060
it's a huge security
risk for most agencies.

00:21:38.060 --> 00:21:39.560
So sometimes, the
better way for you

00:21:39.560 --> 00:21:43.140
to contribute-- in fact, often,
the better way to contribute

00:21:43.140 --> 00:21:47.260
is to be a donor and to
help here if you can.

00:21:47.260 --> 00:21:48.595
ADAM GREEN: Excellent.

00:21:48.595 --> 00:21:50.720
So I want to bring you back
to Google for a second.

00:21:50.720 --> 00:21:52.546
We have this mantra,
don't be evil.

00:21:52.546 --> 00:21:53.920
We all like to
think of ourselves

00:21:53.920 --> 00:21:55.660
as really good people.

00:21:55.660 --> 00:21:59.600
But pretty much all of
us have a tiny slice

00:21:59.600 --> 00:22:01.967
of unspeakable evil
sitting in our pocket

00:22:01.967 --> 00:22:03.800
right now-- the minerals
that go into these,

00:22:03.800 --> 00:22:06.370
particularly coltan
mined in the DRC

00:22:06.370 --> 00:22:10.310
is an engine of human misery.

00:22:10.310 --> 00:22:12.110
Why do you think the
industry collectively

00:22:12.110 --> 00:22:14.010
can't get on top of that?

00:22:14.010 --> 00:22:16.150
We did it with diamonds.

00:22:16.150 --> 00:22:19.460
Why not other minerals?

00:22:19.460 --> 00:22:22.780
SAMANTHA NUTT: It's a lot more
complicated than diamonds.

00:22:22.780 --> 00:22:24.950
And I'm not offering
that up as an excuse

00:22:24.950 --> 00:22:26.620
but more of an explanation.

00:22:26.620 --> 00:22:29.169
I mean, you can take a
diamond and look at it

00:22:29.169 --> 00:22:31.460
under a microscope and know
exactly where it came from.

00:22:31.460 --> 00:22:34.490
And so conflict tracing in
that sort of environment

00:22:34.490 --> 00:22:37.740
became somewhat easier
than with coltan.

00:22:37.740 --> 00:22:41.100
I mean, coltan, it's estimated
that the Congo contains

00:22:41.100 --> 00:22:44.350
between 60% to 80% of the
world's coltan deposits.

00:22:44.350 --> 00:22:46.700
It is readily smuggled
across Congo's borders

00:22:46.700 --> 00:22:49.060
and ends up in
international markets.

00:22:49.060 --> 00:22:52.820
It generates hundreds of
millions of dollars in revenues

00:22:52.820 --> 00:22:56.630
and often use towards arms sales
for various Congolese-backed

00:22:56.630 --> 00:22:58.130
military groups
and militia groups

00:22:58.130 --> 00:23:00.190
operating in that unstable
part of the world.

00:23:00.190 --> 00:23:01.981
But by the time it gets
to your cell phone,

00:23:01.981 --> 00:23:04.270
you have no idea whether
it's Congolese coltan

00:23:04.270 --> 00:23:06.420
or any other kind of coltain.

00:23:06.420 --> 00:23:08.130
Chances are, just
based on probability,

00:23:08.130 --> 00:23:10.170
it is Congolese coltan.

00:23:10.170 --> 00:23:12.630
I think, to be honest,
this is an issue

00:23:12.630 --> 00:23:15.850
that the industry itself
needs to actively get

00:23:15.850 --> 00:23:21.000
behind and start to look at
what solutions are viable

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:22.220
and make the most sense.

00:23:22.220 --> 00:23:26.060
A straight-out
ban, unfortunately,

00:23:26.060 --> 00:23:28.580
follows the law of
unintended consequences.

00:23:28.580 --> 00:23:30.850
And under the Dodd-Frank
legislation in the United

00:23:30.850 --> 00:23:34.720
States that required sort
of more accountability

00:23:34.720 --> 00:23:38.620
and companies not to
use conflict minerals,

00:23:38.620 --> 00:23:40.370
what happened was a
lot of American firms

00:23:40.370 --> 00:23:43.200
closed their mines that put
a lot of artisanal miners out

00:23:43.200 --> 00:23:44.026
of work.

00:23:44.026 --> 00:23:45.900
And what happens when
you have no employment?

00:23:45.900 --> 00:23:48.540
You join a militia group because
they are the only employer--

00:23:48.540 --> 00:23:50.990
so again, the laws of
unintended consequences.

00:23:50.990 --> 00:23:54.560
What we really need
is sectoral reform.

00:23:54.560 --> 00:23:57.560
We need to look at how you
fix the climate of impunity

00:23:57.560 --> 00:23:58.720
at the same time.

00:23:58.720 --> 00:24:00.220
You have to come
at it from a number

00:24:00.220 --> 00:24:02.540
of different perspectives.

00:24:02.540 --> 00:24:06.400
It can be done, but none
of that will ever happen

00:24:06.400 --> 00:24:07.900
unless one other thing happens.

00:24:07.900 --> 00:24:10.180
And that's that
the industry itself

00:24:10.180 --> 00:24:13.280
has to be prepared
to confront this

00:24:13.280 --> 00:24:15.590
in an honest and
transparent way.

00:24:15.590 --> 00:24:17.840
ADAM GREEN: The tech industry,
or the mining industry,

00:24:17.840 --> 00:24:18.000
or both?

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:20.380
SAMANTHA NUTT: The entire
industry-- tech and mining

00:24:20.380 --> 00:24:22.220
because the two really
go hand in hand.

00:24:22.220 --> 00:24:23.620
ADAM GREEN: Yeah, and we're
sitting in a very unique place.

00:24:23.620 --> 00:24:25.090
We're at a big tech company.

00:24:25.090 --> 00:24:27.660
And within a 10-block
radius of this office

00:24:27.660 --> 00:24:30.710
is the highest concentration
of mining company headquarters

00:24:30.710 --> 00:24:31.400
in the world.

00:24:31.400 --> 00:24:33.550
So we might be, in this
office, somewhat uniquely

00:24:33.550 --> 00:24:35.100
placed to tackle this issue.

00:24:35.100 --> 00:24:37.600
SAMANTHA NUTT: You are uniquely
placed to tackle this issue.

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:39.950
And every time any
effort has been

00:24:39.950 --> 00:24:43.020
brought about to
introduce legislation

00:24:43.020 --> 00:24:45.350
around this that
would force, frankly,

00:24:45.350 --> 00:24:47.730
mining companies to be more
accountable and transparent,

00:24:47.730 --> 00:24:51.226
it's been met by very heavy
lobbying, expensive lobbying,

00:24:51.226 --> 00:24:52.850
on the part of those
mining industries.

00:24:52.850 --> 00:24:54.052
And it has been shut down.

00:24:54.052 --> 00:24:55.843
ADAM GREEN: Yeah, bill
C-300 got shut down.

00:24:55.843 --> 00:24:56.690
SAMANTHA NUTT: That's right.

00:24:56.690 --> 00:24:58.106
ADAM GREEN: Very
narrowly, though.

00:24:58.106 --> 00:24:59.624
It was only like 10 votes.

00:24:59.624 --> 00:25:01.040
SAMANTHA NUTT: And
then Paul Dewar

00:25:01.040 --> 00:25:02.390
was trying to
introduce legislation

00:25:02.390 --> 00:25:04.100
