00:28:55.090 --> 00:28:57.870
and they are certainly ongoing.

00:28:57.870 --> 00:29:00.075
And I have testified
at the state committee

00:29:00.075 --> 00:29:01.700
of foreign affairs
over the last couple

00:29:01.700 --> 00:29:04.189
of years on a few of
these related issues.

00:29:04.189 --> 00:29:05.980
I think one of the most
significant things,

00:29:05.980 --> 00:29:08.190
though, that Canada can
do and should be doing

00:29:08.190 --> 00:29:10.870
is signing the
Arms Trade Treaty.

00:29:10.870 --> 00:29:14.970
The Arms Trade Treaty was
initially a Canadian led effort

00:29:14.970 --> 00:29:17.580
to try to bring about
international binding

00:29:17.580 --> 00:29:20.450
legislation concerning the
sale, the manufacturing,

00:29:20.450 --> 00:29:23.370
the stockpiling and the transfer
of small and light weapons

00:29:23.370 --> 00:29:24.300
in the world.

00:29:24.300 --> 00:29:27.490
And about two years
ago now, in fact,

00:29:27.490 --> 00:29:29.930
it finally passed through
the United Nations.

00:29:29.930 --> 00:29:32.870
And more than 115 countries
have signed on to it.

00:29:32.870 --> 00:29:36.810
Unfortunately, along
with Russia and China,

00:29:36.810 --> 00:29:39.490
Canada has not yet signed
the Arms Trade Treaty.

00:29:39.490 --> 00:29:42.110
And because we missed
the first deadline,

00:29:42.110 --> 00:29:45.800
now we have to pass a whole
series of pieces of legislation

00:29:45.800 --> 00:29:48.450
before were even
eligible to sign it.

00:29:48.450 --> 00:29:52.320
And there is-- and I'm going to
be very, very clear on this one

00:29:52.320 --> 00:29:52.960
point.

00:29:52.960 --> 00:29:57.290
There is no way that if we had
signed the Arms Trade Treaty,

00:29:57.290 --> 00:29:59.270
we would have been
able to approve

00:29:59.270 --> 00:30:03.480
that $15 billion arms deal to
Saudi Arabia, or to Thailand

00:30:03.480 --> 00:30:04.190
subsequently.

00:30:04.190 --> 00:30:09.360
So now, the current
government has

00:30:09.360 --> 00:30:11.870
committed to signing
the Arms Trade Treaty,

00:30:11.870 --> 00:30:17.800
but there has been no official
deadline prescribed in relation

00:30:17.800 --> 00:30:19.350
to that.

00:30:19.350 --> 00:30:22.750
And because it is contingent
upon these other pieces

00:30:22.750 --> 00:30:25.090
of legislation
falling into place,

00:30:25.090 --> 00:30:27.250
I don't know how long
that's going to take,

00:30:27.250 --> 00:30:30.080
or if it is even going to
be during this particular

00:30:30.080 --> 00:30:31.470
parliamentary cycle.

00:30:31.470 --> 00:30:32.926
I hope that it is.

00:30:32.926 --> 00:30:37.630
It Is absolutely the
right thing to do.

00:30:37.630 --> 00:30:41.690
And as we talk about
reengaging with the world

00:30:41.690 --> 00:30:45.720
and revitalizing our
multilateralist traditions

00:30:45.720 --> 00:30:49.580
as a country, we certainly
need to understand

00:30:49.580 --> 00:30:52.690
that our absence from
the Arms Trade Treaty

00:30:52.690 --> 00:30:56.170
and the reputation, in many
instances, of our mining sector

00:30:56.170 --> 00:30:59.630
and some of the violations
of human rights and labor

00:30:59.630 --> 00:31:05.000
violations in relation to
that, that that has really

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:08.930
thrown some of our
credibility into question.

00:31:08.930 --> 00:31:10.680
And so if we really
want to get there,

00:31:10.680 --> 00:31:15.370
if we want to still be seen as
that strong, vibrant, ethical

00:31:15.370 --> 00:31:17.660
force in the world,
then we do have

00:31:17.660 --> 00:31:19.930
to get some of these
other pieces in order.

00:31:19.930 --> 00:31:22.425
So hopefully, they'll see
that as one in the same.

00:31:22.425 --> 00:31:24.800
ADAM GREEN: We have a lot of
good intentions as a nation.

00:31:24.800 --> 00:31:27.460
We need to start
actually acting on them.

00:31:27.460 --> 00:31:28.490
SAMANTHA NUTT: Yeah.

