Part of the reason why the Arms
Trade Treaty didn't get signed

00:33:18.083 --> 00:33:20.940
is that there simply wasn't
enough public interest

00:33:20.940 --> 00:33:24.070
or concern or outcry that
we hadn't signed it yet.

00:33:24.070 --> 00:33:25.112
And that's a great shame.

00:33:25.112 --> 00:33:27.195
And I think the same applies
to the United States.

00:33:27.195 --> 00:33:29.010
When you have the
majority of Americans

00:33:29.010 --> 00:33:33.200
who are at least
committed to introducing

00:33:33.200 --> 00:33:36.770
certain aspects of gun control
legislation around particularly

00:33:36.770 --> 00:33:40.930
semiautomatic weapons
like the AR-15, people who

00:33:40.930 --> 00:33:43.290
are on a terrorist
watch list-- we're

00:33:43.290 --> 00:33:47.100
talking about people who have
a very clear mental health

00:33:47.100 --> 00:33:49.610
history that would be
deemed to be high risk.

00:33:49.610 --> 00:33:51.530
I mean, that is a
public safety issue.

00:33:51.530 --> 00:33:53.530
ADAM GREEN: People on the
terrorist no-fly list.

00:33:53.530 --> 00:33:55.655
SAMANTHA NUTT: People on
the terrorist no-fly list.

00:33:55.655 --> 00:33:57.010
That is a public safety issue.

00:33:57.010 --> 00:34:01.520
And they are right to be
shaming and embarrassing those

00:34:01.520 --> 00:34:04.640
legislators who cannot get
behind what the majority

00:34:04.640 --> 00:34:06.517
of Americans want.

00:34:06.517 --> 00:34:08.100
ADAM GREEN: Yeah,
even here in Canada,

00:34:08.100 --> 00:34:09.850
we had a member
of parliament who

00:34:09.850 --> 00:34:14.090
was making the case the AR-15
is a perfectly safe device when

00:34:14.090 --> 00:34:15.159
handled properly.

00:34:15.159 --> 00:34:16.210
So is heroin.

00:34:16.210 --> 00:34:17.280
So is plutonium.

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:19.888
We don't let you
have that either.

00:34:19.888 --> 00:34:22.429
And also made the case that it's
a great deer hunting weapon.

00:34:22.429 --> 00:34:25.044
I've never seen anybody
go hunting with an AR-15.

00:34:25.044 --> 00:34:26.710
SAMANTHA NUTT: And
that's a great point.

00:34:26.710 --> 00:34:27.730
And I would add to that too.

00:34:27.730 --> 00:34:30.355
People will often say, well, if
people want to kill each other,

00:34:30.355 --> 00:34:31.590
they're going to find a way.

00:34:31.590 --> 00:34:34.300
And they will cite
different wars

00:34:34.300 --> 00:34:36.294
around the world in
which machetes were used

00:34:36.294 --> 00:34:39.810
and other things to slaughter
hundreds of thousands

00:34:39.810 --> 00:34:40.320
of people.

00:34:40.320 --> 00:34:42.489
But the truth is that in
almost every instance,

00:34:42.489 --> 00:34:45.560
it's having access to those
small weapons that in fact also

00:34:45.560 --> 00:34:48.040
facilitated that
particular slaughter.

00:34:48.040 --> 00:34:50.130
Because usually,
it's people with arms

00:34:50.130 --> 00:34:52.469
that are able to then
move the populations

00:34:52.469 --> 00:34:54.540
or control or prevent
anybody who is trying

00:34:54.540 --> 00:34:55.820
to stop that from happening.

00:34:55.820 --> 00:34:57.560
So the two often
go hand in hand.

00:34:57.560 --> 00:34:58.690
ADAM GREEN: And the case
for making it easier

00:34:58.690 --> 00:34:59.900
isn't a good idea, right?

00:34:59.900 --> 00:35:00.320
SAMANTHA NUTT: No.

00:35:00.320 --> 00:35:00.740
No.

00:35:00.740 --> 00:35:00.920
Exactly.

00:35:00.920 --> 00:35:01.790
ADAM GREEN: They
might find a way,

00:35:01.790 --> 00:35:03.690
but there's not
a lot of kids who

00:35:03.690 --> 00:35:05.904
get like killed by
stray strangling.

00:35:05.904 --> 00:35:07.320
SAMANTHA NUTT:
Well, that's right.

00:35:07.320 --> 00:35:07.890
ADAM GREEN: That's not a thing.

00:35:07.890 --> 00:35:09.056
SAMANTHA NUTT: That's right.

00:35:09.056 --> 00:35:11.900
And you have a
much better chance

00:35:11.900 --> 00:35:15.820
of being able to
stop that person.

00:35:15.820 --> 00:35:18.660
The more automatic that
weapon is, the more violent

00:35:18.660 --> 00:35:20.714
that weapon is, the
greater the destruction.

00:35:20.714 --> 00:35:21.630
ADAM GREEN: Excellent.

00:35:21.630 --> 00:35:25.709
Any other audience questions
or Dory questions, Vera?

00:35:25.709 --> 00:35:28.250
AUDIENCE: So here at Google, we
have employee resource groups

00:35:28.250 --> 00:35:31.460
of which the largest
is Women at Google.

00:35:31.460 --> 00:35:35.310
There's a pretty strong chapter
in our office led by Margo here

00:35:35.310 --> 00:35:38.250
and Nancy sitting
right next to her.

00:35:38.250 --> 00:35:40.430
So the first time
that I saw you speak

00:35:40.430 --> 00:35:43.480
was at the WXN
summit in November.

00:35:43.480 --> 00:35:46.080
You were the keynote at
the awards gala that night.

00:35:46.080 --> 00:35:48.760
And we were all just like
in love with you after that.

00:35:48.760 --> 00:35:51.540
We thought you had a
lot of great perspective

00:35:51.540 --> 00:35:52.390
on life in general.

00:35:52.390 --> 00:35:54.015
And what I loved
about the way that you

00:35:54.015 --> 00:35:57.210
spoke was that it was not,
oh, I'm speaking to the girls.

00:35:57.210 --> 00:35:58.430
This is like among us girls.

00:35:58.430 --> 00:36:01.360
You just had a great
perspective in life in general.

00:36:01.360 --> 00:36:04.160
That being said, I think you
had a lot to say about what it's

00:36:04.160 --> 00:36:06.470
like being in your role,
and going through your life

00:36:06.470 --> 00:36:08.939
being you, being a woman and
having some of the barriers

00:36:08.939 --> 00:36:09.480
that you did.

00:36:09.480 --> 00:36:12.130
So I'd love if you could kind of
talk about that for this group.

00:36:12.130 --> 00:36:12.620
SAMANTHA NUTT: Well, thank you.

00:36:12.620 --> 00:36:13.911
And it's nice to see you again.

00:36:13.911 --> 00:36:15.632
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:36:15.632 --> 00:36:18.090
SAMANTHA NUTT: Look, there's
no question that being a woman

00:36:18.090 --> 00:36:19.465
and doing this
kind of work comes

00:36:19.465 --> 00:36:22.150
with its own set of challenges.

00:36:22.150 --> 00:36:23.830
We're in environments
around the world

00:36:23.830 --> 00:36:27.110
where there's a tremendous
amount of sexual violence,

00:36:27.110 --> 00:36:29.700
huge amount of harassment--
I mean, I've personally

00:36:29.700 --> 00:36:34.730
experienced a great deal
of that myself-- and risk,

00:36:34.730 --> 00:36:37.470
and then trying to
juggle everything.

00:36:37.470 --> 00:36:38.740
I never use the word balance.

00:36:38.740 --> 00:36:40.710
Balance for me is
always such a cliche.

00:36:40.710 --> 00:36:43.880
Because I, without exaggeration,
wake up every day and deal

00:36:43.880 --> 00:36:44.750
with what's on fire.

00:36:44.750 --> 00:36:46.730
And if I can put
out those fires,

00:36:46.730 --> 00:36:49.590
that is a banner day for me.

00:36:49.590 --> 00:36:51.380
So balance, I
think, is something

00:36:51.380 --> 00:36:54.499
that is sort of a mythology.

00:36:54.499 --> 00:36:56.290
You find balance where
you find leprechauns

00:36:56.290 --> 00:36:57.955
and rainbow-colored unicorns.

00:36:57.955 --> 00:37:00.296
ADAM GREEN: Sounds
like a fabulous place.

00:37:00.296 --> 00:37:01.920
SAMANTHA NUTT: But
you know, so that it

00:37:01.920 --> 00:37:03.640
does come with certain risks.

00:37:03.640 --> 00:37:08.800
And for me, the only way
that I have discovered

00:37:08.800 --> 00:37:11.310
to contend with that is
just to stare them down,

00:37:11.310 --> 00:37:14.570
to get back up, and
to get back in there

00:37:14.570 --> 00:37:18.240
and to persevere, to defy.

00:37:18.240 --> 00:37:21.620
And I've been doing
that my entire life.

00:37:21.620 --> 00:37:24.290
And you get that, as
a girl, from the time

00:37:24.290 --> 00:37:25.712
that you're this big.

00:37:25.712 --> 00:37:26.920
Girls can't play in the park.

00:37:26.920 --> 00:37:27.753
Girls can't do this.

00:37:27.753 --> 00:37:28.667
Girls can't do that.

00:37:28.667 --> 00:37:30.000
Well, girls can do those things.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:31.610
And girls are
doing those things.

00:37:31.610 --> 00:37:35.470
And we're going to show you
that we can do them better.

00:37:35.470 --> 00:37:38.750
And that's the message that I
try to convey to young women

00:37:38.750 --> 00:37:41.830
all the time, which
is to speak up,

00:37:41.830 --> 00:37:48.740
to speak out, to be undaunted,
to don't seek permissions.

00:37:48.740 --> 00:37:50.310
In my opinion,
permissions are only

00:37:50.310 --> 00:37:53.110
sought by those who
lack imagination.

00:37:53.110 --> 00:37:57.800
And don't be afraid to screw up.

00:37:57.800 --> 00:38:00.410
And don't worry so much about
whether people like you.

00:38:00.410 --> 00:38:03.160
I'm sure there's an entire
fleet of people out there

00:38:03.160 --> 00:38:04.970
who can't stand me.

00:38:04.970 --> 00:38:07.330
And I know there is
because, in fact, I

00:38:07.330 --> 00:38:10.570
hear from them on Twitter
quite often, especially

00:38:10.570 --> 00:38:11.920
some of those NRA folks.

00:38:11.920 --> 00:38:14.010
They love me.

00:38:14.010 --> 00:38:20.020
And I think that if we
don't hear enough, really,

00:38:20.020 --> 00:38:22.980
women's voices.

00:38:22.980 --> 00:38:24.920
And we don't role model
enough, and we don't

00:38:24.920 --> 00:38:27.840
mentor that enough, I think.

00:38:27.840 --> 00:38:29.490
And so for all of
you here as women

00:38:29.490 --> 00:38:31.170
who are in the tech
industry, I think

00:38:31.170 --> 00:38:35.180
it's really incumbent on
you, too, to be out there

00:38:35.180 --> 00:38:37.490
and to be talking
about your experiences

00:38:37.490 --> 00:38:40.370
and to be getting other
young women involved,

00:38:40.370 --> 00:38:42.600
and to be defying
those stereotypes.

00:38:42.600 --> 00:38:45.664
Because when I first
started in this work,

00:38:45.664 --> 00:38:48.080
there were hardly any women
going in and out of war zones.

00:38:48.080 --> 00:38:49.630
There were hardly
any-- you know,

00:38:49.630 --> 00:38:53.500
war was always seen as
traditionally a male domain.

00:38:53.500 --> 00:38:56.260
And now, I'm astonished every
time I walk into the office,

00:38:56.260 --> 00:38:59.840
and we have so many more women
in our office than we do men.

00:38:59.840 --> 00:39:04.070
And they're definitely the
visible minority in our office.

00:39:04.070 --> 00:39:06.399
And that's great.

00:39:06.399 --> 00:39:07.940
That is great,
especially when you're

00:39:07.940 --> 00:39:10.670
talking about working with
civilians in war zones,

00:39:10.670 --> 00:39:16.510
that usually, the ones who
are most impacted by war

00:39:16.510 --> 00:39:19.320
are civilians, primarily
women and children.

00:39:19.320 --> 00:39:22.470
So having women on the front
lines of those conversations

00:39:22.470 --> 00:39:26.810
trying to do something about
it is critical to our success

00:39:26.810 --> 00:39:28.630
and to eventually
eradicating the problem.

00:39:32.810 --> 00:39:34.620
ADAM GREEN: In your
book in the intro,

00:39:34.620 --> 00:39:36.880
you mentioned that
you don't think

00:39:36.880 --> 00:39:40.770
that war is a part of
the human condition

00:39:40.770 --> 00:39:42.150
and that there is hope.

00:39:42.150 --> 00:39:44.410
After reading it and
listening to your TED talk,

00:39:44.410 --> 00:39:47.570
I'm just struck by how
complicated these issues are.

00:39:47.570 --> 00:39:48.626
What keeps you hopeful?

00:39:52.380 --> 00:39:54.080
SAMANTHA NUTT: A
couple of things.

00:39:54.080 --> 00:39:56.540
But I would say I don't
fear that complexity.

00:39:56.540 --> 00:40:01.030
I think that part of it
is there aren't always

00:40:01.030 --> 00:40:04.010
easy fixes and easy answers.

00:40:04.010 --> 00:40:07.102
And we mislead people when we
pretend that that isn't true.

00:40:07.102 --> 00:40:09.060
ADAM GREEN: Despite what
campaign promises say.

00:40:09.060 --> 00:40:10.350
SAMANTHA NUTT: Despite
what campaign promises

00:40:10.350 --> 00:40:11.770
are out there, right?

00:40:11.770 --> 00:40:15.350
And I think that for all
of us, as we move forward,

00:40:15.350 --> 00:40:18.720
it is important to be more
sophisticated around what works

00:40:18.720 --> 00:40:19.710
and what doesn't work.

00:40:19.710 --> 00:40:22.440
And that it is complicated
and it's time for us

00:40:22.440 --> 00:40:23.600
to embrace that complexity.

00:40:23.600 --> 00:40:25.880
So I would say partly that.

00:40:25.880 --> 00:40:27.550
But for me,
ultimately what I find

00:40:27.550 --> 00:40:33.150
most hopeful is that every day
in War Child in our office,

00:40:33.150 --> 00:40:38.110
we are surrounded
by people who are

00:40:38.110 --> 00:40:44.310
a testament to what can
be done with compassion,

00:40:44.310 --> 00:40:48.880
and some ingenuity, and
concern, and a sense

00:40:48.880 --> 00:40:50.380
of strong global citizenship.

00:40:50.380 --> 00:40:54.280
We hear from people
who are in our programs

00:40:54.280 --> 00:40:56.380
where it really has
changed their lives.

00:40:56.380 --> 00:40:59.300
We hear from staff who
run those programs who

00:40:59.300 --> 00:41:03.750
helped build those programs
just how important our work is

00:41:03.750 --> 00:41:07.240
to their community, and
how respected they feel,

00:41:07.240 --> 00:41:11.210
and how engaged they
feel, and that ours

00:41:11.210 --> 00:41:14.847
is a true partnership-- that
we're not coming in and telling

00:41:14.847 --> 00:41:16.430
them what to do, but
we're asking them

00:41:16.430 --> 00:41:18.500
what they want to do.

00:41:18.500 --> 00:41:21.850
And that they feel
valued in the process.

00:41:21.850 --> 00:41:25.090
And so whenever I find
myself extremely frustrated,

00:41:25.090 --> 00:41:27.090
which is often-- and it's
never about the things

00:41:27.090 --> 00:41:27.900
that you would expect.

00:41:27.900 --> 00:41:29.300
We're dealing with
security situations

00:41:29.300 --> 00:41:30.966
all the time which
are very frustrating.

00:41:30.966 --> 00:41:33.370
But it's often seeing
a fantastic program

00:41:33.370 --> 00:41:35.210
like the one we have
in eastern Congo

00:41:35.210 --> 00:41:38.330
that survives on
fumes because it's

00:41:38.330 --> 00:41:41.150
so hard to mobilize public
interest for that war

00:41:41.150 --> 00:41:44.980
now that it's almost 20 years
old despite how devastating it

00:41:44.980 --> 00:41:45.680
has been.

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:49.270
That's the stuff that
keeps me up at night.

00:41:49.270 --> 00:41:51.380
But I get up, and I
pushed through that sense

00:41:51.380 --> 00:41:56.710
of cynicism and frustration
because people depend on us.

00:41:56.710 --> 00:42:00.260
And it always has seemed
very self-indulgent to me

00:42:00.260 --> 00:42:02.610
to say, oh, this
work is exhausting.

00:42:02.610 --> 00:42:03.770
I want to do it anymore.

00:42:03.770 --> 00:42:07.340
I mean, we've got people
around the world that get shot

00:42:07.340 --> 00:42:09.500
at on their way to
work, whose children

00:42:09.500 --> 00:42:12.730
can't go more than two blocks
because they'll be raped.

00:42:12.730 --> 00:42:17.270
In South Sudan where all of
our staff and program partners

00:42:17.270 --> 00:42:19.584
had to flee to
the refugee camps.

00:42:19.584 --> 00:42:22.000
And within two days of them
arriving at the refugee camps,

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:23.330
they said, we're
going to keep going.

00:42:23.330 --> 00:42:24.480
And we went, well,
hang on a second.

00:42:24.480 --> 00:42:26.130
We're still trying to figure
out where the stuff is.

00:42:26.130 --> 00:42:27.790
The whole office has
been burned and torched.

00:42:27.790 --> 00:42:28.530
They're like, no, no.

00:42:28.530 --> 00:42:29.155
We're here now.

00:42:29.155 --> 00:42:30.720
We're good to go.

00:42:30.720 --> 00:42:34.510
And that is extraordinary.

00:42:34.510 --> 00:42:39.090
And it's breathtaking
when you experience it.

00:42:39.090 --> 00:42:44.850
And you know, it makes
me really hopeful.

00:42:44.850 --> 00:42:46.480
And that's why I
get up every day.

00:42:46.480 --> 00:42:49.280
ADAM GREEN: That's fantastic.

00:42:49.280 --> 00:42:51.566
Vera, how are we doing for time?

00:42:51.566 --> 00:42:54.530
VERA: [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:54.530 --> 00:42:55.930
ADAM GREEN: OK, excellent.

00:42:55.930 --> 00:43:00.490
So in that case, I'm
going to leave it on that.

